"{\"uid\": \"salon.com-2024-07-30-you-dont-know-about-art-or-history-jodie-sweetin-on-olympics-remarks-like-candace-cameron-bures\", \"text\": \"The Tanner sisters from \\\"Full House\\\" are bickering, and this time it's not about cereal or the TV remote.  Jodie Sweetinhas responded after her TV sister and co-star\\u00c2Candace Cameron Bure\\u00c2\\u00a0said that a particular part of the\\u00c22024 Paris Olympicsopening ceremony served to\\u00c2\\\"blaspheme and mock the Christian faith.\\\"\\u00c2  Conservatives like Bure, Rob Schneider,Elon Musk and House Speaker Mike Johnsonall took issue with a tableau that featured drag performers, dancers and actors lined up against a long table. Later,\\u00c2\\u00a0French actor and singer Philippe Katerine descended onto the table from a giant silver food platter as the Greek god Dionysus. Right-wing critics said the performance mocked Leonardo da Vinci's most popular work, \\\"The Last Supper.\\\"  The interpretation of the Greek God Dionysus makes us aware of the absurdity of violence between human beings.#Paris2024#OpeningCeremonypic.twitter.com/FBlQNNUmvV  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 The Olympic Games (@Olympics)July 26, 2024    In twoInstagramstories, Sweetin seemingly made a dig at Bure. In one post, Sweetin wrote, \\\"Tell me you don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t know about art or history without TELLING me you don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t know about art or history\\\" with a\\u00c2\\u00a0video attached mocking people who misinterpreted the opening ceremony.  Also, to clear up the confusion with the performance, Sweetin explained in her Instagram story the history of the feast of Dionysus.  \\\"The drag queens of the Olympics were re-creating the feast of Dionysus, not 'The Last Supper.' And even if you thought it was a Christian reference \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 what's the harm? Why is it a 'parody' and not a tribute? Can drag queens not be Christian too?\\\" Sweetin stated.  Copyright \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026 Salon.com, LLC. Reproduction of material from any Salon pages without written permission is strictly prohibited. SALON \\u00c2\\u00ae is registered in the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office as a trademark of Salon.com, LLC. Associated Press articles: Copyright \\u00c2\\u00a9 2016 The Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed.  DMCA Policy  By subscribing, you agree that Salon will automatically charge you at the then-current rate (currently $9.95/month or $95/year) each month/year until you cancel. Log in to your account anytime to cancel prior to renewal date and avoid future charges.  Your current signup type is\"}"